## Extension 4 — Turboprop and Turboshaft Variant

### What it means
A turboprop extracts almost all the turbine work as shaft power to drive a propeller, with a small residual jet thrust from the exhaust. A turboshaft (used in helicopters) extracts all of it. The thermodynamic cycle is the same as a turbojet — only the power extraction and thrust calculation change.

### What to add
- A **power turbine** stage downstream of the gas generator turbine
- Propeller efficiency η_prop as a parameter
- Shaft power output [kW] and equivalent shaft horsepower [eshp] as outputs
- Thrust rewritten as: `F_total = F_jet + (P_shaft × η_prop) / V_flight`

### How to get there
1. Add a second turbine call in `turbojet.py` after the existing gas generator turbine — this is the free/power turbine
2. The power turbine extracts the remaining enthalpy drop down to near-ambient pressure
3. Modify `calc_nozzle()` to handle a low-pressure exhaust (most of the energy is already extracted)
4. Add propeller efficiency and shaft power to the output dictionary

### Why this matters
Turboprops dominate regional aviation and military trainers. A turboshaft model is directly relevant to helicopter propulsion and, increasingly, hybrid electric propulsion where the gas turbine drives a generator.

