## Extension 5 — Emissions Estimation

### What it means
Cantera's `equilibrate("HP")` already computes the full post-combustion species composition — CO₂, H₂O, CO, NOx, unburned hydrocarbons are all there in `gas[4].X`. Turning this into an emissions model requires almost no additional physics.

### What to add
- Extract species mole fractions from the combustor exit gas object
- Compute **Emission Index** [g pollutant / kg fuel] for NOx, CO, CO₂, H₂O
- Add emissions outputs to the API response and frontend display
- Sweep emissions vs. TIT, equivalence ratio, and altitude

### How to get there
1. After `gas[4].equilibrate("HP")` in `turbojet.py`, read `gas[4]["NO"].X`, `gas[4]["CO"].X` etc.
2. Convert mole fractions to emission indices using molecular weights and fuel flow
3. Add to the output dictionary — this is a 20-line addition to the existing code

### Why this matters
Emissions are increasingly a certification and regulatory driver. NOx in particular has strict ICAO CAEP limits. Being able to estimate EI_NOx as a function of combustor temperature and equivalence ratio is directly useful in preliminary design.

