## Extension 7 — Surrogate Model / Machine Learning Layer

### What it means
The turbojet model takes 5–40 seconds per point. Parameter sweeps across a 3D design space (CPR × TIT × η_c) become impractical. A surrogate model — trained on cycle analysis outputs — can evaluate the same space in microseconds, enabling optimisation and uncertainty quantification.

### What to add
- A sweep runner that samples the design space (Latin Hypercube or grid) and stores results
- A regression model (Gaussian Process, neural network, or polynomial response surface) trained on the sweep data
- A fast `predict()` function that replaces `calc_thrust()` for optimisation purposes
- Uncertainty bounds on predictions

### How to get there
1. Use the existing `/api/turbojet/sweep` endpoint to generate a training dataset — vary CPR, TIT, η_c, altitude, Mach across their ranges
2. Export via the CSV endpoint
3. Train a `scikit-learn` Gaussian Process or `tensorflow` neural network on the dataset
4. Wrap in a new `surrogate.py` module with the same interface as `calc_thrust()`
5. Validate: compare surrogate predictions against held-out Cantera simulation points

### Why this matters
The pattern — high-fidelity simulation generates data, ML learns the mapping, surrogate enables fast design space exploration — is one of the most widely adopted approaches in modern aerospace design. It is used in compressor blade optimisation, airframe aeroelastics, and full mission optimisation. Building it on top of a cycle analysis tool is a natural and well-trodden path.

### Useful tools
- `scikit-learn` — GaussianProcessRegressor, MLPRegressor
- `scipy.stats.qmc` — Latin Hypercube sampling
- `openturns` — uncertainty quantification

